WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.160
When you think

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:03.900
about the way that we are rolling out
AI in healthcare,

00:00:03.900 --> 00:00:06.560
it's the same way we rolled out
EMRs 20 years ago.

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:09.400
Twenty years ago, we just let the market
do whatever it wanted, right?

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:12.900
Now there are 117 EMR systems
in Kentucky

00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:14.840
and not a single one
talks to each other.

00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:16.120
That is a real number.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:21.360
And so what if we—and, and—we are facing
a healthcare crisis,

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:24.000
the scope of which we can't even
comprehend right now,

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:28.540
because of the big beautiful bill,
210,000 patients in Kentucky

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:30.820
are about to lose
their health insurance, right?

00:00:30.940 --> 00:00:33.240
There are 35 hospitals that are now
under threat of closure.

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:35.600
If AI is going to
revolutionize healthcare,

00:00:35.860 --> 00:00:36.520
who does it for them?

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:38.380
Because they could barely
keep the lights on.

00:00:39.620 --> 00:00:41.480
So let's do it for them, right?

00:00:42.180 --> 00:00:44.580
What if we provided healthcare AI
as a service?

00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:48.380
One single institution—the state—
we get it together,

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:49.760
we do it all, right?

00:00:50.280 --> 00:00:53.200
Every predictive model,
remote patient monitoring,

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:55.020
we do the whole thing.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:57.680
We find all of those cancers.
We bring them in.

00:00:57.980 --> 00:00:59.600
All of your A1Cs greater than nine

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:01.600
who haven't followed up
with their primary care doctor

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.800
in a year, two years—
bring them back in.

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:06.280
All of that health data exists

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:07.780
on your health information exchange.

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:10.040
What if we build
an intelligence layer

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:11.420
that sat over the top of that,

00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:13.660
constantly crawling through that data,

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:16.540
looking for signals,
looking for ways to make you better?

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:18.660
It's the OSCE grader.

00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:20.600
It's just got a different face.

00:01:21.380 --> 00:01:22.240
And so this was the pitch.
